    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Hue name for one of the three primary additive colors; that portion of the spectrum lying between green and violet, with a wavelength of about 420 to 490 nanometers, which is the shortest wavelength range of the three primary colors. The term may refer to any of this group of colors that vary in lightness and saturation. An example of blue color in nature is that of a clear sky during the day.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000093795/Encyclopedia Britannica Online (2002-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000048174/American Heritage Dictionary (1982)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Eén van de drie primaire additieve kleuren; dat deel van het spectrum dat zich bevindt tussen groen en violet, met een golflengte tussen ongeveer 420 en 490 nanometer, het kortste golflengtebereik van de drie primaire kleuren. De term kan verwijzen naar alle in helderheid en verzadiging variërende kleurschakeringen binnen deze groep kleuren. Voorbeelden van de kleur blauw in de natuur zijn de kleur van een heldere lucht overdag.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>指色相名稱，為三種加色法原色的其中一種。在光譜上，藍色介於綠色和紫色之間，波長在420奈米到490奈米之際；在三原色裡，藍色的波長最短。在藍色系中帶著不同明度與飽和度的色彩，皆可稱為「藍色」。舉例來說，晴朗天空的藍色，就是大自然中的一種藍色。
</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079740/AS-Academia Sinica data (2014-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Nome de matiz para uma das três cores aditivas primárias; aquela porção do espectro que fica entre o verde e o violeta, com um comprimento de onda de cerca de 420 a 490 nanômetros, que é o menor intervalo de comprimento de onda das três cores primárias. O termo pode se referir a qualquer um deste grupo de cores que variam em luminosidade e saturação. Um exemplo de cor azul na natureza é o de um céu limpo durante o dia.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Portuguese</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000316/CVAA-BR</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
